  <div class="q-grid">
    <div class="q-card">
      <div class="q-id">Q-01 · Data Architecture</div>
      <div class="q-txt">How many active monitoring stations feed this dataset, and where are they located in the city?</div>
      <div class="q-why">The data pattern suggests a single station. If true, there is no way to distinguish industrial hot spots from residential exposure or assess spatial inequality in pollution burden.</div>
      <span class="q-tag tag-b">Data Gap</span>
    </div>
    <div class="q-card">
      <div class="q-id">Q-02 · Missing Data</div>
      <div class="q-txt">What explains the 221 days of missing AQI readings, particularly the 115 gaps in 2022?</div>
      <div class="q-why">Were sensors offline during smog emergencies, exactly when data is most critical? Equipment failure during high-pollution events would systematically underestimate the crisis and undermine trend analysis.</div>
      <span class="q-tag tag-b">Data Quality</span>
    </div>
    <div class="q-card">
      <div class="q-id">Q-03 · Institutional Mandate</div>
      <div class="q-txt">Which ministry or agency has the authority to declare and coordinate a smog emergency in Punjab?</div>
      <div class="q-why">The PDIA framework asks us to identify the authoriser. Without a clear mandate holder, data triggers no action. The governance failure may be more structural than technical.</div>
      <span class="q-tag tag-p">Governance</span>
    </div>
    <div class="q-card">
      <div class="q-id">Q-04 · Source Attribution</div>
      <div class="q-txt">Has any source apportionment study been conducted to quantify the share of PM2.5 coming from crop burning, brick kilns, transport, and transboundary inflows?</div>
      <div class="q-why">Without this, any intervention is a guess. Shutting schools during peak smog does nothing to reduce emissions. We need to know which levers to pull.</div>
      <span class="q-tag tag-m">Causal</span>
    </div>
    <div class="q-card">
      <div class="q-id">Q-05 · Policy Effectiveness</div>
      <div class="q-txt">Which policy interventions were implemented during this five-year period, and have their effects been evaluated against the AQI record?</div>
      <div class="q-why">The dataset spans five years of smog emergency declarations, factory closures, and agriculture directives. Without an intervention log, this rich dataset cannot tell us what actually works.</div>
      <span class="q-tag tag-p">Evidence Gap</span>
    </div>
    <div class="q-card">
      <div class="q-id">Q-06 · Health Linkage</div>
      <div class="q-txt">Is there a matched dataset linking daily AQI to hospital respiratory admissions, school absenteeism, or mortality in Lahore?</div>
      <div class="q-why">The human cost remains invisible in this data. A linked health-AQI dataset would create the political urgency needed to mobilise resources and would be internationally publishable.</div>
      <span class="q-tag tag-g">Missing Data</span>
    </div>
    <div class="q-card">
      <div class="q-id">Q-07 · Transboundary</div>
      <div class="q-txt">Is there any data-sharing or joint monitoring agreement with the Indian Punjab government or international bodies covering the shared airshed?</div>
      <div class="q-why">Back-trajectory models suggest a significant share of winter smog enters from the east. No unilateral policy can fully address a transboundary problem. This is both a diplomatic and a technical opening.</div>
      <span class="q-tag tag-p">Diplomacy</span>
    </div>
    <div class="q-card">
      <div class="q-id">Q-08 · Citizen Access</div>
      <div class="q-txt">Is this AQI data publicly accessible in real time, and are health-protective advisories issued automatically at threshold crossings?</div>
      <div class="q-why">Data held in government databases creates no behaviour change and no political pressure. Real-time public access via a web dashboard or SMS alerts transforms monitoring into a public accountability tool.</div>
      <span class="q-tag tag-p">Transparency</span>
    </div>
    <div class="q-card">
      <div class="q-id">Q-09 · Scalability</div>
      <div class="q-txt">What is the current monitoring infrastructure budget, and is there appetite to deploy a low-cost sensor network to complement the reference stations?</div>
      <div class="q-why">Low-cost sensors (PurpleAir, AirQino, Clarity) cost USD 200 to 2,000 versus USD 50,000+ for reference stations. A hybrid network of 10 to 15 nodes could map spatial heterogeneity at a fraction of the cost.</div>
      <span class="q-tag tag-m">Scaling</span>
    </div>
    <div class="q-card">
      <div class="q-id">Q-10 · Proposal</div>
      <div class="q-txt">Would the government consider a pilot "Smog Intelligence Dashboard" integrating AQI, satellite fire detection, weather forecasts, and health data for the 2024 – 2025 season?</div>
      <div class="q-why">This would be a concrete, time-bound deliverable creating cross-ministry coordination, public accountability, and an evidence base for international climate finance. It is an entry point, not a final solution: aligned with PDIA's iterative logic.</div>
      <span class="q-tag tag-p">Proposal</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

